oai_dc:dc.dc:title: A Retrospective Study of Risk Factors that Affect Outcomes in Bovine Cesarean Sections (1998-2003)
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Newman, K. D.
Anderson, D. E.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: cesarean sections
risk factors
clinical impression
emphysematous presentation
fetal delivery
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Bovine cesarean sections are one of the most commonly performed procedures in bovine practice with a variety of outcomes. A number of risk factors that affect outcomes have been proposed, but substantiated by clinical impression alone. The purpose of this retrospective study was to determine whether there was a difference between elective, emergency non-emphysematous and emergency emphysematous presentations. The objective was to compare whether the ability to exteriorize the uterus during fetal delivery and/or calf viability at the time offetal delivery have effects on outcome.
